column1: Will Montenegro become a full NATO member before 1 January 2018?
column6: ['Foreign Policy']
column11: This question was closed as "yes" with an end date of 5 June 2017 (NATO, NBC News, Reuters). Montenegro's accession to NATO can happen when all 28 members have ratified the accession protocol (BBC, NATO, Balkan Insight, VOA News, Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberity , European Western Balkans). Last month the Senate overwhelmingly backed the expansion of NATO to allow Montenegro to join the alliance, hoping to send a message that the United States will push back against Russian efforts to increase its influence in Europe.

There are two things that could now prevent Montenegro joining NATO; Spain has not yet ratified the offer; the last opinion poll in Montenegro (Dec 2016) there was a small majority against joining. Spain is expected to ratify before 17th May, which will mean all members will have ratified by May. The option polls showed that there were around 20% who did not say they were either for or against NATO. Now that the US has ratified I would guess that some of the "don't knows" will decide that they do want to join. (Human nature is that you are usually keener to join a club if they have agree to let you in.) In any event the decision in Montenegro is that of the government, that has not agreed to a referendum, and the government wants to join NATO. A possible problem could be that 39 (out of 81) MPs have been disputing the October 2016 election, so the government has only a small majority over a Pro-Russian anti-NATO Opposition.

This is an interesting and difficult question to answer. On the face of it the only thing missing is the formal ratification of Montenegro as a full NATO member. If procedure is observed, this could be achieved by end of May. Indeed Western diplomats consider it a "done deal". However, some factors make the process less than straightforward.
https://europeanwesternbalkans.com/2017/03/09/us-senate-will-ratify-protocol-in-shortest-period-possible/

Right now Montenegro is just waiting on three countries, Spain, the Netherlands, and the USA. While Trump may have feelings on the subject, treaties like this are approved by the senate with a 2/3 majority and it is pretty clear to me that the senate has the numbers to pass this. So it is simply a matter of following procedure in the remaining countries, unless Trump crumbles and gives into yet another Russian adventure.

President Putin doesn't confide in me, but I'd bet this issue isn't a make-or-break for him. Our guy will make Montenegro promise to pony up their share of the bucks, the US will allow them to join the club, and Putin will bluster but that's all. If that's the case--an assertion for which I have no direct evidence--agreeing to accession will provide President LIttlefingers and his band of merrymakers a cheap and harmless way to pretend that our boy is not in their boy's pocket.
